{
  "document_id": "prov-29",
  "title": "Proverbs 29",
  "type": "study-bible",
  "translation": "Oxford",
  "blocks": [
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-2",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 2,
      "text": "When the righteous are in authority, the people rejoice; but when the wicked rule, the people groan."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-h1kj-4",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "2 : See 28.12n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 29
      },
      "verse_start": 2,
      "verse_end": 2
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-3",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 3,
      "text": "A child who loves wisdom makes a parent glad, but to keep company with prostitutes is to squander one's substance."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-h1kj-5",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "3 : See 10.1n. , see 31.3; Sir 9.1–9.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 29
      },
      "verse_start": 3,
      "verse_end": 3
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-4",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 4,
      "text": "By justice a king gives stability to the land, but one who makes heavy exactions ruins it."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-5",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 5,
      "text": "Whoever flatters a neighbor is spreading a net for the neighbor's feet."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-6",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 6,
      "text": "In the transgression of the evil there is a snare, but the righteous sing and rejoice."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-h1kj-6",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "5–6 : , see 28.23n. The wicked ensnare themselves; see 1.10–19; 12.13.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 29
      },
      "verse_start": 5,
      "verse_end": 6
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-7",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 7,
      "text": "The righteous know the rights of the poor; the wicked have no such understanding."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-h1kj-7",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "7 : , justice and legal rights due to them (e.g., 31.5,8; Deut 17.8; Isa 10.2; Jer 5.28).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 29
      },
      "verse_start": 7,
      "verse_end": 7
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-8",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 8,
      "text": "Scoffers set a city aflame, but the wise turn away wrath."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-9",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 9,
      "text": "If the wise go to law with fools, there is ranting and ridicule without relief."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-10",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 10,
      "text": "The bloodthirsty hate the blameless, and they seek the life of the upright."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-11",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 11,
      "text": "A fool gives full vent to anger, but the wise quietly holds it back."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-h1kj-8",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "11 : , see 12.16n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 29
      },
      "verse_start": 11,
      "verse_end": 11
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-12",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 12,
      "text": "If a ruler listens to falsehood, all his officials will be wicked."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-13",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 13,
      "text": "The poor and the oppressor have this in common: the Lord gives light to the eyes of both."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-h1kj-9",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "13 : See 14.31n. , i.e., give life; see 15.30.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 29
      },
      "verse_start": 13,
      "verse_end": 13
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-14",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 14,
      "text": "If a king judges the poor with equity, his throne will be established forever."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-h1kj-10",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "14 : See 16.12–13n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 29
      },
      "verse_start": 14,
      "verse_end": 14
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-15",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 15,
      "text": "The rod and reproof give wisdom, but a mother is disgraced by a neglected child."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-h1kj-11",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "15 : , see 10.13n. , see 1.23n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 29
      },
      "verse_start": 15,
      "verse_end": 15
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-16",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 16,
      "text": "When the wicked are in authority, transgression increases, but the righteous will look upon their downfall."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-h1kj-12",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "16 : See 28.12n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 29
      },
      "verse_start": 16,
      "verse_end": 16
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-17",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 17,
      "text": "Discipline your children, and they will give you rest; they will give delight to your heart."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-h1kj-13",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "17 : , lit., “delicacies for your appetite” (Heb “nephesh”; see 2.10n.).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 29
      },
      "verse_start": 17,
      "verse_end": 17
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-18",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 18,
      "text": "Where there is no prophecy, the people cast off restraint, but happy are those who keep the law."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-h1kj-14",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "18 : (Heb “ḥazon”), i.e., vision or revelation; see 1 Sam 3.1; Ps 74.9; Lam 2.9; Ezek 7.26. , see 28.4n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 29
      },
      "verse_start": 18,
      "verse_end": 18
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-19",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 19,
      "text": "By mere words servants are not disciplined, for though they understand, they will not give heed."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-20",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 20,
      "text": "Do you see someone who is hasty in speech? There is more hope for a fool than for anyone like that."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-h1kj-15",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "20 : See 26.12. Proverbs cautions against (e.g., 19.2; 21.5), particularly when speaking (e.g., 10.19; 17.27).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 29
      },
      "verse_start": 20,
      "verse_end": 20
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-21",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 21,
      "text": "A slave pampered from childhood will come to a bad end."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-22",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 22,
      "text": "One given to anger stirs up strife, and the hothead causes much transgression."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-h1kj-16",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "22 : See 15.18n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 29
      },
      "verse_start": 22,
      "verse_end": 22
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-23",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 23,
      "text": "A person's pride will bring humiliation, but one who is lowly in spirit will obtain honor."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-h1kj-17",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "23 : , see 11.2n. , i.e., humble, see 3.7n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 29
      },
      "verse_start": 23,
      "verse_end": 23
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-24",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 24,
      "text": "To be a partner of a thief is to hate one's own life; one hears the victim's curse, but discloses nothing."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-h1kj-18",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "24 : , i.e., the victim's charge of the crime, which requires those who know something about the matter to testify or be subject to punishment (Lev 5.1; cf. Judg 17.2–3).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 29
      },
      "verse_start": 24,
      "verse_end": 24
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-25",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 25,
      "text": "The fear of others lays a snare, but one who trusts in the Lord is secure."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-26",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 26,
      "text": "Many seek the favor of a ruler, but it is from the Lord that one gets justice."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-27",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 27,
      "text": "The unjust are an abomination to the righteous, but the upright are an abomination to the wicked."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-h1kj-1",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "25.1–29.27: These are other proverbs of Solomon that the officials of King Hezekiah of Judah copied.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 29
      },
      "verse_start": 1,
      "verse_end": 27
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-h1kj-2",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "28.1–29.27: Similar to 10.1–15.33, a series of largely antithetical proverbs that contrast the righteous and wicked. Persistent is concern about power and just government.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 29
      },
      "verse_start": 1,
      "verse_end": 27
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-29-h1kj-19",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "27 : , see 3.32n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 29
      },
      "verse_start": 27,
      "verse_end": 27
    }
  ]
}